posts.com:
Start by reading the gospel. There's a great audiobook called Land of Havilah on youtube and spotify. I'd recommend starting with the book of Matthew as it seems to be the most complete of the four eyewitness books chronicling Jesus' life (Mark, Matthew, Luke and John). Mark is the shortest so you could also start there.

I find some sort of commentary helps when you're starting out, the guy from Land of Havilah is a charming southern fellow and he makes things pretty simple.

Start with the New Testament, then do the Old Testament.

I personally read the four gospel books, then Genesis and Exodus, then the Pauline letters. St. Paul left his home and went country to country teaching Christianity to the gentiles (this story is told in the Book of Acts), then wrote letters concerning the nature of God and the logic behind Christianity to the churches he established there. These letters are called the epistles. So for example the Book of Romans is Paul's letter to the church in Rome, the Book of Thessolonians is his letter to the Thesselonians, etc.

The Old Testament has so-called Wisdom books, which lay out Christian thought in a similar way. Ecclisiastes and Proverbs are the most substantial of these, with Ecclisiastes sometimes being called the most beautiful book in western literature. It's very "zen'". There are also many books of history and literary analogy in the old testament, but it's more important to read the New Testament first because it will help you understand the meaning of these a lot better.

Some of the Old Testament can honestly be kind of dry, you dont have to read it right away. For example Leviticus is notoriously boring because it's basically a legal text describing the law for the followers of Moses, most of which are no longer followed eg. animal sacrifice, instructions on how to build the temple and holy grail, etc. The historical books of the OT focus less on God than long ass historical accounts, who begat who, etc.

>Why can't theses idiots just make new characters?
John K of Ren and Stimpy fame, described the animation industry of the 1980s as a hellscape for artists because executives had no interest in creating anything new. If it wasn't based on a toy, or a previous property, then they wouldn't fund the project.
That changed in the 90s, and for a good 20 years we saw many legendary animations being made.
But let's go back to what I said previously, "if it wasn't based on a toy, or a previous property", why would executives think this? Rather simple, because people know about old properties and therefore trust them to be good, which means more viewers, which means more money.
The difference between then and now, is that investors are so high on being woke, that they have to resurrect old properties, and then make the characters brown.

addendum from what i copied yesterday for other anons:
For anyone that's interested, having played with adjusting individual layers of block merges I have some notes:

base_alpha : text interpretation. 0 for model A, 1 for model B. Middle values tend to yield poor results if models are extremely dissimilar. If one model is a specialty model, favor that one.

Output side:
fine details, shading = 1,2
Hand Data, rough details = Layer 3
These layers seem to affect contrast but I'm not sure what else = Layer 5,6 (?)
face shape data = layer 7
body proportions = layer 8
Posing, placement, body shapes = layer 9
placement and framing = layer 10, 11
Scene contents = layer 12. Masks appeared, some characters varied in age, purple hair, fewer clothes, greater breast size variety
Layer M = the bottom layer, M is not for multiplier. If merging models that are significantly different you need to pick 1 or 0 to get the bottom layer from one model or the other.
